Food blame for European inflation
The main reason for the increase in inflation in the euro area was the rapid rise in food prices.
In the 13 countries of the eurozone, inflation was higher than expected in November - after 2.6 percent in October, an annual rate of inflation of 3.1 percent was recorded, as reported by the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts are based on only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
In contrast to the American, British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not reduced the lead rate.
The ECB strives to keep the inflation rate below two per cent, or at least close to the two per cent mark.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in the twin mill: inflation had to be "agreed" in order to exclude the need for action later.
At 3.3 percent, the rate of inflation in Germany reached a twelve-year record high in November; in Spain, the rate rose from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
The increase in inflation in the euro area was responsible for the increase in food and energy prices.
The MATIF wheat quotations rose by 88 percent, and the price for soybeans also reached a record high since 1973.
Food oil and dairy products were also significantly expensive in 2007.
The world market price for crude oil rose by 52 percent this year - last month the price per barrel of black gold reached nearly 100 US dollars.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 to 2.5 percent in 2008, but is projected to decrease to 1.9 percent in 2009.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts estimate a 3-percent inflation rate, but estimate the annual average rate at 2.1 percent.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to reduce interest rates twice.
