In many places, disinfectants are saved
Today, more than a thousand infections have been recorded in hospitals due to improper handling of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in the hospitals, the overloading of the beds, the overloading of the staff - all factors that are not at all conducive to the containment of the infections, according to the leading physician of the National Epidemiology Centre.
In many places the disinfectants are also saved.
A MRSA infection was recently diagnosed in the traumatology department of the János hospital.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year there was already a similar infection here.
The injured person of a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but a little later the man had to return with an MRSA infection. Since then, an important surgery has not been performed due to the bacterium that is still in the patient's body.
Until December 10th this year, multi-resistant pathogen infections were reported from hospitals in 1094 to the National Nosocomomialis Surveillance System, according to Karolina Böröcz, the leading physician of the National Epidemiology Center.
So many infections caused by multi-resistance pathogens have been recorded in hospitals with certainty, but the dark number is likely to be higher.
Approximately two thirds of the infections (683 cases) were triggered by MRSA, the Staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about one third of the people in its nose without causing any disease.
SA-related infections (such as sore throat, almond inflammation, inflammation of the skin or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
However, if the funds are too high or used improperly, the well-responsive bacteria produce antibiotics-resistant, which spread rapidly in hospitals under appropriate conditions.
Especially in patients with a weakened, or permanently functioning immune system, but also in the elderly, or in patients with low body weight, these bacteria may cause severe infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i. e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of the János hospital, MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents are part of the daily routine.
One should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, said Tibor Nyulasi - MRSA is just not there where it is not sought.
Resistant to antibiotics
"These patients are isolated, the caregivers wear rubber gloves and masks in the care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for the treatment" - says Tibor Nyulasi.
Although patients are being examined for MRSA during their hospitalisation, infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling too rare
The majority of infections caused by MRSA in hospitals would be avoidable, but the current prevailing conditions and circumstances would be unfavourable for the inhibition of the emergence or spread of the multi-resistance pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
After this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and old-age homes, the hospitals should investigate the patients admitted and immediately isolate MRSA-infected patients.
In Hungarian hospitals, however, microbiological sampling is not practised so often.
Not least because there are no grants from the state health insurance fund for this investigation.
Most cases would therefore not be brought to light until the patient already has a significant MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the epidemiology centre.
There are strict recommendations from the European Union on the use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines in Hungary for the treatment of certain infections and disease images.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, i.e. microbiological tests are necessary to prevent resistance to the drug, but this directive is not always complied with by hospitals.
Among the outpatients, or patients in the primary care, microbiological samples were even more rare, says Karolina Böröcz.
The disinfectants are saved
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most often transferred by caregivers from one patient to another.
This is precisely why hand washing, or wearing gloves and masks are of great importance, but there are also significant deficiencies in hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but in local hospitals there is not always the possibility to isolate the infected patient.
The rooms are often even crowded, the beds are close to each other, although there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them from an epidemiological point of view.
As Karolina Böröcz further points out, unfortunately, in the less well-off hospitals it appears that disinfectants are saved, there are few caregivers, many patients - all the factors that actually favour the development of infections.
According to Karolina Böröcz, such infections are shown to be much less common there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped where these protective measures are observed.
Government programme against MRSA
Getting MRSA infections into control causes the health insurance huge costs, so they are fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its containment, was recorded in the government programme.
After first signs, the program is successful - as published data prove, the trend of MRSA infections in England is decreasing.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has identified the prevention of multi-resistance pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of infections in hospitals as one of its priorities.
