Fodor and the six Hungarian percentages
As Environment Minister Gábor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will be continued by the ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries discuss the Bali roadmap, which sets out emission reduction measures for the period after 2012, i.e. after the Kyoto Protocol expires.
There is currently a heated debate between industrial and developing countries.
The US has already indicated that they do not want to negotiate specific figures, but they would be willing to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other major issue at the conference is whether the industrialised countries are willing to support developing countries financially and technologically in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement was also reached on the support of developing countries.
The adjustment fund under the Kyoto Protocol is to be managed by a 16-member Council, expected to be included in the UN Global Environmental Facility (GEF), as reported in the "Piac és Geut".
Six per cent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Environment Minister Gábor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to maintain its pioneering role in global climate protection measures and to reach a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister said that the EU would reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (as measured by 1990 values), regardless of whether the "agreement after 2012" would be successful, or not. The Union would even be prepared to make a 30% reduction if other major industrial states in the world, or developing countries, are also willing to meet their commitments according to forces and responsibly.
Gábor Fodor stressed that the objective of the states that had acceded to the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2 percent, whereas the EU had already committed itself to a reduction of 8% with its then 15 member states.
The standard for Hungary is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6% compared to 1985-87 - a requirement that the country will fully meet, as can be read in the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The commitment is high on Bali - after all, the long-term international climate policy agreement must be completed within two years, otherwise it would certainly not enter into force until 2012, in which case the reduction project set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not follow a new international emission reduction system, the importance of which was also highlighted in its recent report by the IPCC, the International Nobel Peace Prize-winning UN Scientific Committee on Climate Change.
This would delay the reduction of emissions, and the increase of the Earth's average temperature by more than 2°C would be inevitable, which, according to scientists, would result in extremely serious and irreparable consequences.
British Army Reels on YouTube
UK Army units have published recordings of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan for the purpose of increasing popularity on the video portal.
First of all, the British Air Force (RAF) discovered YouTube for itself: Special units stationed in Afghanistan have been uploading videos on operations conducted against the Taliban since March 2006, reports the BBC.
The miniature cameras shot on helmets are controlled at the air force base in Kandahar and then sent to London, where they are placed on the Internet.
Political message inevitable
Air Force soldiers have already contributed 139 such recordings, their "channel" has been viewed more than 75,000 times.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered under "defenceheadquarters" in spring 2007 to publish videos on Iraqi and Afghan operations, but also the British Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Commonwealth Office) and the International Peace Forces (MNFI) stationed in Iraq have their own YouTube channels.
Use in Afghanistan
Originally, the Air Force has published the videos with the aim of recruiting soldiers, and, as the Ministry of Defence says, the contributions also serve the purpose of informing the population about the actual objectives of foreign operations.
According to defence expert Gordon Mackenzie to the BBC, propaganda of this kind is almost free of charge, but these videos always carry a certain degree of political message in their own right to the existence of the military measures decided by the government.
American advertising with game
However, the army must also fight against amateur shootings, which, in addition to carefully processed, censored recordings, also create the net - such as those showing the death of the soldiers: the somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films speak of the losses at most, but the bloody sides of the war are not shown.
Of the war scenes in Iraq and Afghanistan, by the way, many videos already in use have been loaded onto the platform, but the British have only recently discovered this "gift".
The Americans, however, advertise in a slightly different way, namely with the free downloadable shooting game "America's Army", in which the player can slip into the soldier's skin as part of a more or less life-like simulation.
