Political Capital: Hungarian Guard Increases State Risk
According to the Risk Analysis Division (Risk Analysis Division) of Political Capital, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, founded this August with the support of the "Movement for a Better Hungary", have increased the risk of Hungary and the region in several respects.
Among other things, the Institute's "Risk Warning Report" states that, in connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the highest political risk is the "enhancement of existing ethnic tensions between the Gypsy and non-Gypsy population in Hungary, which could even lead to violent ethnic conflicts in the short term".
The main reason for this was the strategy of the Hungarian Guard, which is probably aimed at provocation of such an argument, according to the Research Institute.
As reported, this is seen as a failure on the part of the political leaders: "People of public life have left the discussion of the Roma issue to representatives of radical political groups who have now built up their political strategy on the Roma-Hungary contrast".
It is believed that this would exacerbate the problem, make reasonable dialogue impossible, promote extremities, and increase the likelihood of violent conflicts.
The Research Institute also believes that the activities of the Hungarian Guard, not least because of the enormous attention given by local and foreign media, "have seriously damaged Hungary's image abroad, especially as regards confidence in stability and democratic maturity".
We remember that since autumn 2006, the reorganization of radical and extreme right groups in Hungary has been steadily on the rise, so that since summer 2007 several "national self-defense association" organisations have been established.
"These groups are in common that they define themselves as civil organizations, while openly boasting of preparing their members for defence tasks - sometimes armed - (catastrophe protection, state defence, order-keeping), calling upon the inadequacy of the police, the army, or the state itself," it said.
And on the other hand, all of this happens in accordance with that method, which tries to camouflage various political and party-based aspirations as a bourgeois initiative.
The emphasis on the civil character and the form of the association is therefore not merely the circumvention of legal barriers that could arise in the course of the registration at the court - it is also a political strategy.
As can be seen from the analysis, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are also a risk-raising factor for relations with neighbouring countries.
"In recent months the Hungarian Guard has been cited as a potential source of danger in several neighbouring countries, as some ultranationalist politicians from certain neighbouring countries see in the emergence of the Hungarian Guard the confirmation of their own anti-Hungary policy.
All of this has an impact on the political stability of the region" - it was said.
From the point of view of the research institute, the establishment of the Hungarian Guard is not a single phenomenon in Central Eastern Europe, so the political risk for the whole region has grown.
As reported, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are similar to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, whose foundation was announced in August 2007 by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
In the background of the formation of the Bulgarian Guard, the Roma mass exodus took place in a district of Sofia (Krasna Poljana).
The BNU has taken the incidents immediately to the occasion of the establishment of the National Guard, arguing that the aim of the organization is "national protection".
