Holidays are not everywhere holidays
In Hungary, holidays are regulated by law, so that the practice of redeploying the working days around the holidays has now established itself, but the coming year gives us less such days.
Also in the EU and in America, something else is understood as "Feast Day".
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between public holidays and working days.
Unemployed days are usually church holidays, or are related to important historical events.
For example, we also celebrate New Year: both the last day of the old, as well as the first day of the new year are unemployed days - the latter alone so that the New Year's celebrations can rest.
All year round we have a total of fourteen holidays.
The public holidays are the 15th of March, which commemorates the revolution of 1848, and the 23rd of October, the anniversary of the Revolution of 1956.
On August 20th, the foundation of the state, celebrated on May 1st, we commemorate our dead on November 1st and 2nd.
In addition, there are every two holidays at Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our public, national or religious holidays rarely fall to a weekend, the practice of the "working day shift" has proved itself in cases where we would only work one day before or after the holiday.
The price of the extended weekends, however, is that we have to work well on Saturdays before, or go to school.
When this day, which falls before or after the holiday, is finally to be worked out, the Minister of Labour has been set out in his own regulation for many years.
The legislation applies equally to all employers and employees, public servants and public service officials.
Only companies and establishments in which the operation is continued without interruption, i.e. also on public holidays, are excluded.
Today, the working order is only confused by the holidays at the end of the year: from December 24th, life will stand here formally, as most will take time off for the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve, or the special holiday for it.
In the next year, more holidays will fall into the middle of the week, or to the end of the week, so that there will be fewer redisposables in working days than this year.
The calendar is first put "on the head" around the day of work, so that people can stay at home for four days.
Saturday, April 26th will be a working day so Friday, May 2nd can be a rest day.
The second re-disposal is linked to the holiday on October 23rd: on Saturday, October 18th you will have to work on Friday, October 24th.
At the end of the year, however, the holiday will be marked by no more than 24 December, after everything is and will remain, even if New Year's Eve falls on a Wednesday.
