And it happened that one of the collectors that can be folded up like accordions was damaged by a taped cable at a length of about a meter.
The restructuring was stopped in order not to damage the collector any more.
The astronauts, who originally left the space shuttle for a check-up and then had to repair another solar collector whose rotational system was faulty, were forced to dedicate themselves to the damaged collector.
And Scott Parazynski was selected to walk around at the end of the 30-metre long remote-controlled arm of the space shuttle, which had been installed at the station to carry out the repair.
He is one of NASA's best spacewalkers.
Large, resilient, very skillful, he has a well-developed torso and long arms.
The 46-year-old trained doctor was therefore selected to operate on the injured solar collector.
After carefully examining the damage, he cut through the faulty cable and fixed some kind of rail on the damaged spot.
He was supported by a second Spacewalker, who remained near the lock, and, from inside, by the other astronauts, among them Peggy Whitson, commander of the crew.
The tool he used, a mini hockey bat, wrapped with an insulator to prevent an electric blow on the solar collectors that generate several hundred volts, had the astronauts on board the station designed and built.
When the action was over, Scott Parazynski waited until the collector was fully refurbished before counting his tools and returning to the station.
