After more than 60 years of confidential treatment, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which document the fates of 17,5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents of the archive, which have been housed in Bad Arolsen for a total length of 27 km, could not be seen until now, unless with a humanitarian intention, i.e. individual and name-based, i.e. at the request of a former victim or his family.
In May 2006, the eleven States, including Germany, France, Israel and the United States, entrusted with their administration, agreed to make them available to researchers and historians.
After the ratification process of this Decision has been completed, the opening has been valid since yesterday.
Heikle Information
Historians' access to Bad Arolsen will enable them to carry out research, especially on the deportations of prisoners, the inmates of the concentration camps and the health status of the forced workers, explains Reto Masters, head of this archive, which is managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (CICR).
Until recently, several states, including Germany, were opposed to making these name-related documents available to the public, due to the sensitive nature of certain information.
For example, the alleged homosexuality or the mental disability of some deportation victims.
The inmates of the concentration camps or the warrants issued by the Gestapo were gathered after the war for a practical reason: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labour, and possibly to provide them with evidence of their arrest to pave the way for them to be compensated.
Even today, more than 300 permanent staffed tens of thousands of personal requests are working in Bad Arolsen.
However, part of the scientific community shows only a limited interest in accessing Bad Arolsen.
One cannot expect anything fundamentally new in these documents, explained Pr. Wolfgang Benz, Head of the Research Center for Anti-Semitism at the Technical University of Berlin, 2006.
