New concerns about natural gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A new price dispute erodes between Ukraine and Russia, increasing the risk that Russian exports of fuel will be affected to Western Europe.
Most of the Russian exports of natural gas to the European Union (EU) are managed by Ukraine and every dispute between the two nations is observed very closely.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price it has to pay for natural gas, it will charge Russia higher transit fees.
An earlier conflict between the two states last year reduced deliveries to the EU countries.
The recent conflict between Kiev and Moscow takes place at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine has to pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine has to be more calculated as the Group has agreed to pay up to 50% additional for natural gas from neighbouring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say that this could mean that Ukraine has to pay 40% more for the imports of Gazprom.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states in discussions," said Ukraine's economic minister Anatoli Kinakh of the Reuters news agency.
"The changing gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the amount of transit fees [to Western Europe] on Ukraine."
In the last major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom reduced deliveries to Ukraine.
This led to a case of exports to Western Europe, which drastically increased prices.
Russian gas is one quarter of the European Union's supply.
Russia has the world's largest gas deposits, but much of them remains underdeveloped.
The result is that Gazprom complements its own stocks with gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
NHS "must control foreign workers"
The Scottish State Health Service must improve checks on the criminal record of workers from outside Europe, said a member of the control body outside.
The recommendation of Chief Financial Controller Robert Black came after a foreign doctor in Scotland was brought in Zusammenhang with the attack on Glasgow Airport in June.
Black also expressed concern that the Scottish public health service did not have a precise idea of the number of his foreign employees.
However, his report pointed out that other important controls were carried out correctly in a sample of five health authorities.
The principal financial controller investigated staff recruited outside the European Economic Area following the attack on Glasgow Airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after an off-road car was driven through the doors of the main airport terminal.
He was one of three doctors who appeared in a video transmission at Old Bailey in October and was charged with the suspected car bombing in the UK.
It is expected that the State Health Service will carry out checks in advance of the employment of foreign employees to ensure that they have the necessary qualifications, experience and authorizations to work in the United Kingdom.
Although the health authorities use Disclosure Scotland to review criminal records, the Agency does not have the competence to obtain this information outside the UK.
The main auditor's report now states, in addition to other recommendations, that the Management Board should take up guidelines on criminal records that help employers in checks in different countries.
"Although we have found evidence of these checks in some personnel documents, they have not been carried out routinely."
Black said that the Scottish health authorities would closely follow their investigation guidelines prior to the appointment, but added: "Our report identifies areas where the system can be improved to ensure that accurate information on the number of foreign health service staff is available."
BMA Scotland Chairman Dr. Peter Terry said it was "extremely unlikely" that investigations prior to the appointment of potential NHS employees would identify people who could commit future terrorist attacks.
"The report states that the NHS Scotland's current pre-production tests are working well and it is not clear what added value the recommendations will provide," he said.
The Scottish health authorities say that they currently have 1,161 foreign employees, the vast majority of whom are doctors and nurses.
However, the financial controller warned that the number is likely to be higher, also because the board of directors had problems identifying those employees who were left for an indefinite period of time.
The investigation continued to show that established control procedures have been largely complied with by the NHS authorities in Ayrshire, Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian.
These include passport, work permit and qualification checks.
the Scottish Government is currently reviewing its policies and guidelines for pre-employment checks for foreign personnel in the NHS.
Nicola Sturgeon, Secretary of Health, said: "It was my concern to carry out this work in the face of the terrorist attack on Glasgow Airport."
It added that the Scottish Government, in conjunction with the health authorities, would take into account the recommendations of the report and would ensure that the best practices in updated guidelines on control investigations would be reflected in advance of the recruitment of all employees - including those from abroad - whose publication is planned next month.
