After a few months of doubting the authenticity of Andy Warhol's Brillo Boxes in 1968, internal research in the Moderna Museet in Stockholm is now coming to a sobering conclusion: The six "Brillo-Boxes", which the former museum director Pontus Hultén has done as a gift to the Moderna Museet in 1995, are copies - and probably most of the approximately one hundred other Brillo-boxes of the "Type Stockholm", which are in circulation on the international art market.
The history is shattered, a confusing chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964 Warhol created his first "Brillo-Boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the cardboard boxes of the "Brillo" soap powder.
An exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet 1968, with Warhol's consent, exhibited hundreds of Brillo boxes from cardboard: These were not from Warhol (for cost reasons) but were delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
They were not works of art, but their models, they were mere pieces of exhibition.
At the same time, in 1968, Warhol probably granted permission to produce a few Brillo wooden crates in Sweden, which, however, were not issued in the Moderna Museet.
Contemporary witnesses now speak of about fifteen crates, which at that time have rightly been incorporated into the art and auction history as authorized original Andy-Warhol-Brillo-Boxes with the name "Type Stockholm".
Some of them have achieved more than $100 000 dollars at auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that it had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, and that Warhol had then left it to him.
In fact, Hultén's 105 boxes were only produced in Malmö in 1990 for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
At that time Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, Chief Conservator at Moderna Museet, has also examined three of the Swedish private holdings in addition to the six museum's own Brillo-Boxes, two of which were manufactured in Stockholm in 1968: their press strips were first grounded and smelted, after which white oil was applied with a brush.
The structure of the 1990 copies, on the other hand, reveals that the paint was applied directly to the press panel with a paint roller without primering - and this is not about oil paint, but about acrylic paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes," says the director of the Moderna Museet, Lars Nittve: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come to a different conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibition material."
As early as July, the Authentication Board announced that it would follow the "serious accusations" raised in the case of soap powder boxes.
But since then one has been hiding there in unswerving silence.
Rebellious Soldiers in Manila Give Up
In the Philippines, rebel soldiers have abandoned themselves in a hotel in Manila, demanding the overthrow of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
He could not answer bloodshed, said leader Antonio Trillanes, who accused the president of corruption and electoral fraud, reporters in the hotel.
Government-faithful soldiers had previously stormed the hotel under tear gas.
The approximately two dozen soldiers had been hiding in the building for hours.
About half of them were in court on Thursday for a failed coup attempt in 2003 - among them Trillanes.
He used the negotiation to suddenly settle down with about 30 sympathizers.
The military police, who were supposed to guard him, apparently had crossed over to him and joined his mutiny.
They invaded the Peninsula Hotel and demanded the overthrow of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Loyal government troops locked up the district around the main hotel.
The President called for an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
The National Security Consultant Norberto Gonzales condemned the action of the soldiers.
"People have enough," said Trillanes.
"We call on the people to join us."
General Danilo Lim, who previously commanded the elite unit of the Scout Rangers, said that other army units wanted to join the march shortly.
Government critics had called for major demonstrations against the President for Friday.
Their government has been overshadowed by accusations of corruption for months.
Manila's financial district was already the main scene of attempted mutiny by about 200 military members against Arroyo in 2003.
The uprising failed after almost 24 hours of the army's refusal to join.
Since 1986 there have been at least seven coup attempts against democratically elected governments in the Philippines.
